Q: What does the war between Kuwait and Iraq have to do with Kuwait’s independence from Britain?

A: Premier Sheik Abdullah Al-Salem Al-Sabah was opposed to the war with Iraq and wanted to ask Britain to mediate.

Q: Which figure came to mind when you were asked to comment on Sheik Abdullah Al-Salem Al-Sabah?

A: If we look at Premier Sheik Abdullah Al-Salem’s principled views and the extent of his status in society, we find that he can be compared to Shaikh Zayed.

Q: What is the “geopolitical location” of Kuwait in the region?

A: The Jamaat Al-Mosul (Isa Al-Hamad/Abass Al-Sabah) Society was established in the Iraqi capital.

Faisal Al-Maamari was one of its members. So was the then mufti of Shammar in Kuwait, Al-Habioulah Al-Eryani.

Q: Sheikh Ihsan’s picture was published in 1962. Do you have information on him, Associate Professor Dr Alawi Al-Othman?

A: Sheikh Ihsan Al-Faleh was in Abu Dhabi in 1956.

He was expelled from Kuwait for allying himself with the Third Ali Mubarak military post commander, Abdullah Al-Kubaisi.
